<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-07-16T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-07-16T00:00:00-05:00" n="364" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d364">
                    <opener><seg rendition="#center">No. 7.</seg></opener>
                    <head><persName type="from">Mr. Mason to Earl Russell</persName>.—(Received July
                        16.)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>24 <hi rend="smallcaps">Upper Seymour Street,</hi>
                                <hi rend="italic">Portman Square,</hi></placeName>
                            <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-07-16"><hi rend="italic">July</hi>
                                16, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                    <p><hi rend="smallcaps">My Lord:</hi> I have the honor to transmit herewith a
                        list of vessels arriving at the port of Nassau (Bahamas) from ports alleged
                        to be blockaded in the Confederate States of America, from the 18th of July,
                        1862, to the 2d of June, 1863, being 102 in number.</p>
                    <p>This list was sent to me by the commercial agent of the Confederate States at
                        Nassau, and, besides the minuteness of his description, is entitled to be
                        received as an authentic document.</p>
                    <p>I have no instructions to make any new communication to your lordship on the
                        subject of the alleged blockade, but I desire to place the document on the
                        files of the foreign office as part of the history of the occasion,
                        interesting certainly to my government, and perhaps to the government of her
                        Majesty.</p>
                    <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>J. M. MASON.</signed></closer>
